  "prompt": "Can a constitutional amendment be deemed unconstitutional by the Supreme Court?",
  "response": "No, the Supreme Court cannot declare a constitutional amendment unconstitutional. Once an amendment is ratified and becomes part of the Constitution, it is considered valid and binding. The process of amending the Constitution is outlined in Article V, and as long as an amendment is adopted in accordance with that article, it is treated as legitimate.\n\nHowever, the Supreme Court can interpret the Constitution and its amendments, which means the Court can rule on the legality and application of laws or actions taken under those amendments. This can sometimes lead to contentious interpretations, but the amendments themselves are not subject to being declared unconstitutional in the way that laws can be.",
